commit.message: Fix #45.
add wcovby and mop
add covers symbol and blackboard letters

Add `\specializes →` ⤳ abbreviation

For https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib/pull/10914

Abbreviations `\/` and `\quot` for `⧸`

[Mathlib PR 10501](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib/pull/10501) introduces `⧸` as an infix operator producing quotient types. I propose that we use `\/` and `\quot` as abbreviations for this operator.
Add support for imenu for some common constructs

Add option to turn of automatic syncing

Sometimes it is desirable to not have the server be synced on each
change. One example is when you are writing a complicated type signature
for a lemma. I have often found that I don't need any feedback until
I've finished writing it out because the type signature will be nonsense
until then.

Extract the delay in lean-server-change-hook into a variable

A low value on the delay in the call to `run-at-time' in
`lean-server-change-hook' can introduce a lot of typing latency,
especially in larger proofs. By extracting the value into a variable
users can choose the delay to suit their needs.

commit.message:
feat(*): port to eldoc handling of emacs 28

Retain existing behaviour for emacs ≤27 users, but for emacs 28 users
port eldoc handling to its newer versions. Note: for emacs 28 users,
`lean-show-type`, for some reason, always opens the docs in a new buffer
instead of using the echo area.

Replace deprecated dash-functional dependency

Dash 2.18.0 now subsumes dash-functional.

Change functor arrow to rightwards harpoon

There are many ways to input rightwards double arrow already, and
mathlib makes use of rightwards harpoon for its notion of a functor.
The VSCode mode for Lean uses rightwards harpoon for its \functor, so
to make things easier for emacs users it might be good to make
\functor mean the same thing.
chore: require lean-info in lean-type

Make sure each file byte-compiles by itself with no errors

The cl- changes are needed for compatibility with gccemacs, which
motivates this commit. I added three other requires while at it.

Clarifying the readme, and a typo

The `add-to-load-path` is a [spacemacs
function](https://github.com/syl20bnr/spacemacs/blob/master/core/core-load-paths.el#L11),
so it might be better to mention the vanilla emacs function in the
readme.

This commit also corrects a small typo in a function's document string.

Reuse the window for info buffers

This is a patch for a possible window management feature.  The current
functionality has it so that both `C-c C-g` (`lean-toggle-show-goal`)
and `C-c C-n` (`lean-toggle-next-error`) create their own windows.
However, there can be a lot of overlap in information between them, so
I find myself toggling windows frequently.  This, unfortunately,
messes up my window layout because of the behavior of
`display-buffer`.  While this can be fixed somewhat with a
user-defined `display-buffer-alist`, I thought it would be nicer to
have these buffers share a window.

This commit changes `lean-toggle-info-buffer` to look for a window
containing an info buffer, and reuse it if one exists.  But, if one
exists and it is for the requested type of buffer, then that window is
closed, implementing the toggling functionality.

Change the requires-pattern in helm-lean

Helm seems to require that the `:requires-pattern` be an integer
rather than anything non-nil.  This commit changes the argument from
`t` to `1`, which should give exactly the intended functionality.

I did not track down whether this was caused by a new version of helm
or of emacs.  All I tracked down is that there is a comparison with
`t` that results in the error `(wrong-type-argument number-or-marker-p t)`
when trying to do `C-c C-d`.

Modified overlays for the message boxes

The `C-c C-b` message boxes had a couple of quirks that this commit
addresses.  The first is that they were placed *after* comments that
followed a command.  For example, it might show up as

> #eval 1+2
> -- This was an example of eval
> │ 3

rather than

> #eval 1+2
> │ 3
> -- This was an example of eval

It seems the basic reason this happens is that `lean` itself gives a
very conservative end position for a message, after having consumed
both whitespace and comments.  The `lean-message-boxes--make-overlay`
already took into account whitespace, so this commit introduces a new
function `lean-message-boxes--in-comment` to give it the ability to
also take into account characters that are part of a comment, which
seems to be a widely used method that is reliable so long as
`font-lock-mode` is on.

The second quirk is that a command at the very end of a file would not
show its message box unless there was an additional newline.  This
seems to have been because `lean-message-boxes--make-overlay` would
try to add the overlay to beyond the end of the file.  Rather than
moving the point forward, this commit changes the behavior to prefix
the overlay's string with a newline, which has seemed to be more
reliable.  There are some other small changes to allow the cursor to
be in a sensible position with respect to the overlay.

Increase memory limit for lean from 1G to 4G

The current default (1G) is too low, especially when editing files in
large projects like mathlib, so increase to the more reasonable 4G.

Allow displaying Lean goal in another frame

### Description
This change allows displaying the Lean goal in another window if desired.

### Problem

Before this change, if the `*Lean Goal*` buffer is in another frame, it won't display the Lean goal. This makes it hard to use `lean-mode` with `frames-only-mode`. `lean-mode` checks whether the `*Lean Goal*` buffer is visible in order (I assume) to avoid wasting time updating a buffer that's not visible. However, before this change, the `*Lean Goal*` buffer needed to be in the focused frame in order to authorize updates.

### Proposed solution

Instead of checking whether the `*Lean Goal*` buffer is active in the current frame, check whether it's active in any visible frame.

### Alternative solutions


The other options are presented by the `ALL-FRAMES` argument to `(get-buffer-window)`:

> BUFFER-OR-NAME may be a buffer or a buffer name and defaults to
the current buffer.

> The optional argument ALL-FRAMES specifies the frames to consider:

> - t means consider all windows on all existing frames.

> - visible means consider all windows on all visible frames.

> - 0 (the number zero) means consider all windows on all visible
    and iconified frames.

> - A frame means consider all windows on that frame only.

"Iconified" means an icon of the frame is visible rather than the actual frame contents, so that's not desired. An alternative could be using `t` (all frames), but that defeats the optimization. It might be a good idea for some use case I haven't thought of. `'visible` seems like a reasonable compromise in any case.
